<ns3260:section xmlns:ns3260="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.introduction.j2eeApis.jta">

  <ns3261:title xmlns:ns3261="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Transaction API and Java Transaction Service</ns3261:title>
  <ns3262:para xmlns:ns3262="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Transactions provide a mechanism for specifying atomic processes, i.e. processes
    which have to be completed either as a whole or if an element of the process fails, the
    entire transaction has to be undone.
  </ns3262:para>
  <ns3263:para xmlns:ns3263="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Furthermore resources involved in one transaction may be temporarily in an invalid or
    uncertain state. During this period access to these resources may be restricted to one
    transaction only.
  </ns3263:para>
  <ns3264:para xmlns:ns3264="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The Java Transaction API (JTA) is a standard API for managing transactions. It
    supports demarcating, committing and rolling back transactions. Transactions across
    distributed resources is supported via two-phase commit.
  </ns3264:para>
  <ns3265:para xmlns:ns3265="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    A Java Transaction Service (JTS) is an implementation of the JTA.</ns3265:para>
</ns3260:section>